General Q\&A  
**Q:** What libraries can I use?  
**A:** Only: stdio.h, string.h, stdlib.h  
**Q:** Can I use all the functions in string.h?   
**A:** Only the ones we saw in the triguls.  
**Q:** Can I use all the functions in stdlib.h?   
**A:** There is no reason to use more than what we saw in the tirguls, but please notice you may want to use [atoi](https://www.tutorialspoint.com/c_standard_library/c_function_atoi.htm).  
**Q:** Is there any limit on the inputs in the ex?  
**A:** No. all are limitless, but at least one char. \[you can assume that\]  
**Q:** Can I assume anything in the menu input?  
**A:** Sure, assume it is one of the options.  
**Q:** Do I just need to have the same output?  
**A:** No. You also need to free ALL BYTES. even if a single one is leaked, the test result will be 0\.

TVShow \*\*\*database \= NULL;  
int dbSize \= 0;

**database**: (TVShow\*\*\*) A 2D array of pointers to TVShows.  
**dbSize**: (int) The array is always a nXn. dbSize is n.  
YOU ARE NOT ALLOWED TO ADD MORE GLOBAL VARIABLES.

Structs  
You are given a few structs, which you are **not allowed** to change. üôÇ  
We will go one by one and explain each field. You may want to read it once, then read the rest of the document, and come back to reading it again.  
TVShow  
typedef struct TVShow {  
   char \*name;  
   Season \*seasons;  
} TVShow;

**name**: (char\*, dynamically allocated) The name of the tv show.  
**seasons**: (Season\*) The start of the linked list of the seasons for that tv show.

Season  
typedef struct Season {  
   char \*name;  
   Episode \*episodes;  
   struct Season \*next;  
} Season;

**name**: (char\*, dynamically allocated) The name of the season.  
**episodes**: (Episode\*) The start of the linked list of the episodes for that season.  
**next**: (Season\*) The next season for that tv show, or null.  
Episode  
typedef struct Episode {  
   char \*name;  
   char \*length;  
   struct Episode \*next;  
} Episode;

**name**: (char\*, dynamically allocated) The name of the episode.  
**length**: (char\*) The length of the episode, in format of XX:XX:XX \[Hours:minutes:seconds\]  
**next**: (Episode\*) The next episode for that season, or null.

Menus  
We will start the program with printing this menu:  
Choose an option:  
1\. Add  
2\. Delete  
3\. Print  
4\. Exit

On Add, we will print this menu:  
Choose an option:  
1\. Add a TV show  
2\. Add a season  
3\. Add an episode

On Delete, we will print this menu:  
Choose an option:  
1\. Delete a TV show  
2\. Delete a season  
3\. Delete an episode

On Print, we will print this menu:  
1\. Print a TV show  
2\. Print an episode  
3\. Print the array

---

Add  
When a user choose to add, we will print options:  
Choose an option:  
1\. Add a TV show  
2\. Add a season  
3\. Add an episode

On choice of ‚ÄúAdd a TV show‚Äù, we will print:  
Enter the name of the show:  
And then, we will save whatever the user chooses to enter as input. \[only ascii characters though\], when the ‚Äú\\n‚Äù is the one marking the end of the input.  
Please notice, we cannot have the same tv show twice.  
So, if we already have a tv show the user entered, we will print:  
Show already exists.  
How does it work with the array?

1. If we have enough space in the array, we will add it to the array in the correct place.  
2. What is the correct place? We want the array to be ordered, always. so, If we had ‚ÄúFriends‚Äù, ‚ÄúScrubs‚Äù and we just got ‚ÄúBreaking Bad‚Äù, we would put ‚ÄúBreaking Bad" at the first cell \[0,0\], and Friends and Scrubs would shift one to the right.  
3. If not, we will need to realloc the array to be (n+1)x(n+1), when n is the previous dimension. and, shifting all the variables backwards, so we will not have free space between variables.

On choice of ‚ÄúAdd a season‚Äù, we will print:  
Enter the name of the show:  
Enter the name of the season:  
Enter the position:  
When we will wait for the user input between each.  
If the user entered unregistered show, we will print:  
Show not found.  
If the user entered an already registered season for the same show we will print:  
Season already exists.  
*NOTE: only if we already have this name for another season IN THE SAME SHOW.*  
And go back to the main menu.  
Please note: the position can be any no-negative number \[yes, you can assume a none-negative integer\], and we will enter the season in that place in the linked list of the seasons of that show.  
Please note, if the user entered a number that is higher than the number of seasons we have, It is fine and the season will be at the end of the current linked list.

On choice of ‚ÄúAdd an episode‚Äù, we will print:  
Enter the name of the show:  
Enter the name of the season:  
Enter the name of the episode:  
Enter the length (xx:xx:xx):  
Enter the position:  
Otherwise:  
Show not found.  
Season not found.  
Invalid length, enter again:  
Respectively.  
Please note, on ‚ÄúShow not found.‚Äù and ‚ÄúSeason not found.‚Äù We will go back to the main menu immediately.  
While in ‚ÄúInvalid length, enter again:‚Äù we will get a new input from the user, again and again, until they enter it in the correct format.  
What is the correct format?  
0-99:0-59:0-59  
Which means, we are accepting only ‚Äòtwo-digits colon two-digits colon two-digits‚Äô when the first two digits can make only a positive number, up to 99 \[inclusive\]. and the other two digits, can make only a positive number as well, but up to 59 \[inclusive\]. Because we cannot have more than 59 minutes in an hour, and more than 59 seconds in a minute.  
Also, If the user entered an already registered episode for the same season we will print:  
Episode already exists.  
And go back to the main menu.  
---

Delete  
When a user chooses to delete, we will print options:  
Choose an option:  
1\. Delete a TV show  
2\. Delete a season  
3\. Delete an episode

On choice of ‚ÄúDelete a TV show‚Äù, we will print:  
Enter the name of the show:  
And then, we will delete it.  
What does it mean? few things:

1. Free everything related to this show.  
2. Remove the show from the array.  
3. Shift the remaining shows in the array backwards.  
4. If the array can be (n-1)x(n-1) and will still have enough space for all the shows, we will do it, and realloc the array to be (n-1)x(n-1), when n is the previous dimension of the array.

On choice of ‚ÄúDelete a season‚Äù, we will print:  
Enter the name of the show:  
Enter the name of the season:  
When we will wait for the user input between each, and if the user entered unregistered show, or unregistered season, we will print:  
Show not found.  
Season not found.  
Respectively.  
Please note, on ‚ÄúShow not found.‚Äù and ‚ÄúSeason not found.‚Äù We will go back to the main menu immediately.

On choice of ‚ÄúDelete an episode‚Äù, we will print:  
Enter the name of the show:  
Enter the name of the season:  
Enter the name of the episode:  
When we will wait for the user input between each, and if the user entered unregistered input, we will print:  
Show not found.  
Season not found.  
Episode not found.  
Respectively.  
Please note, on each invalid input, We will go back to the main menu immediately.  
---

Print  
When a user choose to print, we will print options:  
Choose an option:  
1\. Print a TV show  
2\. Print an episode  
3\. Print the array

On choice of ‚ÄúPrint a TV show‚Äù, we will print:  
Enter the name of the show:  
And then, we will print it.  
What will we print?  
The name of the show, the Seasons, and the episodes.  
For example:  
Enter the name of the show:  
Chainsaw Man  
Name: Chainsaw Man  
Seasons:  
	Season 0: The third horse man  
	Season 1: Reze arc  
		Episode 0: Boom\! (00:32:59)  
		Episode 1: Bam\! (99:59:59)

Please note, the space before each ‚ÄúSeason x:‚Äù is 1 tab.  
The space before each ‚ÄúEpisode x:‚Äù is 2 tabs. 

On choice of ‚ÄúPrint an episode‚Äù, we will print:  
Enter the name of the show:  
Enter the name of the season:  
Enter the name of the episode:

When we will wait for the user input between each, and if the user entered unregistered input, we will print:  
Show not found.  
Season not found.  
Episode not found.  
Respectively.  
Please note, on each invalid input, We will go back to the main menu immediately.  
What to print on valid input?  
Only name and length. For example:  
Enter the name of the show:  
Chainsaw Man  
Enter the name of the season:  
Reze arc  
Enter the name of the episode:  
Bam\!  
Name: Bam\!  
Length: 99:59:59

On choice of ‚ÄúPrint the array‚Äù, we will print:  
We will immediately print the 2D array. how?  
For example, if we had 2 shows:  
\[Chainsaw Man\] \[Jujutsu Kaisen\]   
\[NULL\] \[NULL\] 

If we had only 1:  
\[Jujutsu Kaisen\] 

**If we had no tv shows:**  
We would print nothing.

In other words, we will print the name of the shows, 1 by 1, and NULL for the empty spaces in the array.  
---

Exit  
We will end the program.  
**Please keep in mind \- we must free all memory we allocated.**
